{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1938011701/0794.xml":{"full_text":"2\nSenate Filibuster\nFails to Halt Work\nOs Congress' Units\nCommittees Active on Wide Range of\nSubjects, Including Reed Nomination i\nBy ARTHUR HACHTEN\n(1.N.5.) Though the Senate today was still in the grip,\nof a bitter filibuster against the anti-lynching bill, action\non a wide range, of measures prevailed in the House and\nin Senate and House committees.\n18-Inch Guns\nTried in Japan\n(1.N.5.) The Navy De-\npartment has received un- j\nconfirmed reports that Japan I\nhas experimented with 1 fl\ninch guns for her battle\nships. testimony before the\nHouse Naval Appropriations\nsubcommittee made public\ntoday, disclosed.\nQuestioned by committee\nmembers as to whether any\nnation is building guns\nlarger than the standard 14\nand 16-inch type. Rear\nAdmiral Furlong, chief of the\nBureau of Ordnance, said:\n\u201cNone that 1 know of. hut\nthere is an unconfirmed re\nport that Japan built an ex\nperimental IS inch gun in\n1936.\u201d\nDAINGERFIELDS\u201d\nEND LEGAL TILT\nMrs. Alice R. Daingerfield, who\n\u00abueri her husband. John S. Bar\nhour Daingerfield, member of a\nprominent Virginia family, sot a\nlimited divorce on grounds of\ncruelty last summer, drooped her\nsuit today in United States Dis\ntrict Court.\nAs a result of his wife\u2019s suit.\nDaingerfield sued E. Pendleton\nTurner, wealthy Washington so\ncialite. for SIOO,OOO damages, al\nleging the latter alienated the at I\nfectjons of his wife. This suit also\nwas dropped last week by Daingcr-\nfield.\nMrs. Daingerfield had accused;\nher husband of cruelty and speci-i\nfled that he frequently drank to\nexcess. The couple were married 1\nin a brilliant ceremony in Balti\nmore on November 16, 1907,\nGifts for Education\nIncrease in Year\nNEW YORK. Jan. 17 (I.f\u2019.S.'.\nPhilanthropists last year gave\nmore money for education and\ngifts but 1 ss for religion, the fine\narts and health, accord ng to fig\nures listed today by the John\nPrice Jones Corporation. Philan-i\nthropic giving for all purposes in\nsix leading cities showed a gain\nof $47,70'\u2019,993 over 1936.\nNew York was first and Boston\nsecond in total gifts and bequests.!\nboth cities showing a gain over;\n1936. Howe/er. totals fell off in\nPhiladelphia Chicago. Baltimore\nand Washington.\nChase Bank Holds\nU. S. Finance Lead\nNEW YORK. Jan. 17 <1.N.5.).!\nThe Chase National Bank con\ntinued to hold first place among I\nthe country's banks as the only\ntwo-billion-dollar bank by showing\ndeposits of $2,069,988,000 at the\nend of 1937. the annual tabula\ntion of the Financial Age pointed,\nout today. Four other banks fall\ninto the billion-dollar class, includ-'\ning the National City Bank, with\n$1,711,552,000 deposits: the Guar-'\nanty Trust Company, with $1,449.\n$07,000: the Bank of America 1\nN. T. S A San Francisco with J\n$1,357,379,000 and the Conti\nnental Illinois National Bank and\nTrust Company, Chicago, with\n$1,006,695,000.\n-jssf <-feriMES\nFobltibed Daily al 1317 H 61. N W\nwith Rumiav IMue u the Wa\u00abhln\u00bbu>\u00bb\nHerald-Tima* _____\nEditorial and Bneinni Phone\nKKpnblle 1234\nCnterad tht roti OUnt atningtaa\nD. C-. at ttcond-clast mail maiter_\neiunor Patterion Kdllnt and PuhHaber\nWilli*. C. Shell!. General Manager\nBATES BT CABBIBB IN WASHINGTON D.'c\nAND SUBURBS\nDally and\nDali, Buna* j Hunda,\nOM Tw 15-20 8520 \u00abW-4\u00bb\n81i Month* 160 2 60 6.2*\nThtea Mantht 1-30 1.30 1-60\nOn,\u201cHontb M\no\u2014 We*4r 10 .10 JO\nBATWItT MAIL I'OR VIRGINIA. MARYLAND.\nVTRUT VIRGINIA AND NORTH CAROLINA\nDail, and\nDall, Bunday Hun day\nfear $6 00 SB.OO 112.00\nZr MttMlM 8.5\u00ae 8.50 1.00\nWM gODtM 1.80 1.80 I 50\nSw Mwm I M\n\u25a0~OTHEB BTATBS. CANADA AND MEXICO\nDally and\nDally Bunday S.inday\nOai Teal \u00bbI SO \u00abT. 2 116.00\nSix Maethi 3 0* S S\" 3 so\nThree Month. 100 >.\u00abO\nOneJAantf.\nAIX UAJT. gUBSCRIPTIONF PATABIB\nAPVANO\nTilnthenf D.U\nNo signs of a break in the i\ntigtv over the anti-lynching bill\nappeared. Administration leaders\ncontinued to bide their time be-1\nI fore directing pressure to smash\nthe opposition.\nGLAVIS CALLED\nOfficial Washington watched'\nthe Senate Public Lands Com-!\nmH tee s investigation into wire\ntapping and espionage by the\nInterior Department\u2019s secret i|\npolice. Louis R Glavis, former\ndirector of the department\u2019s:\ndivision of investigation, was,\n-called before the committee today.,\nWhile the Senate\u2019s special com\nmittee on unemployment causes\nresumed its healings, the Judic\niary Committee in executive ses\nsion waded through a batch of I\nissues. The Burke resolution call\ning for an investigation of the\nNational Labor Relations Board,\nwas referred to a subcommittee.\nREED NOMINATION UP\nLikewise referred to subcommit\ntees were bi\u2019ls to create four new\ncircuit judgeships and a score of,\nFederal district judgeships. Ju-'\ndiciary branch of the Government!\nwas expected to be considered by\nthe full committee.\nA subcommittee, headed by Sen\nator Logan (D.) of Kentucky,\nplanned to meet shortly to con\nsider President Roosevelt\u2019s nomi\nnation of Solicitor General Stan\nley Reed to be an Associate Jus- i\naice of the Supreme Court, succeed\ning Justice George Sutherland, 1\nwhose voluntary retirement be- I\ncomes effective tomorrow.\nf A favorable report by the Judict-\nary Committee was expected for a I\nbill authorizing retired Supreme]\ni Court justices to sit in courts of J\nthe District of Columbia. Chair-;\nman Ashurst <D.) of Arizona, ex-j\nplained there was some doubt as to\nwhether these justices could assist:\ncourts of the Nation\u2019s Capital.\nTAX HEARINGS PUSHED\nMeanwhile, the House was push\ning toward passage the Treasury-1\nPost Office annual appropriation\nbill, with the Navy supply bill next,\non the agenda. The House Ways.,\nand Means Committee continued]\nhearings on the general tax revi j\n\u2022sion bill.\nSenate-House conferees were ex-\npected to reach a final agreement]\non the farm bill this week and the]\nhousing bill, now in conference,\nwas said to be nearing completion.l\n'At the same time the Senate Ap\npropriations Committee was con- I\nsidering the House-passed inde\npendent offices supply bill.\nA stiff fight has developed over\na House rider to give the President\npower to veto items In any appro\npriation bill. Opposition Senators\nbelieve the only proper way to\ngive the Executive veto power over I\nitems would be through a consti-j\ntutional amendment.\ni\nSpending Sole Slump Cure,\nLaGuardia Tells Senators\niContinued from Page I)\ncooperate with the Government\nduring these times as an enter\ngency.\u201d he said. \u2018For now we\ncan see the need of a vast pub\nlie spending program to sustain\nthe peoples purchasing power.\n\u201cAnd if we can sustain this\npurchasing power we might pull\nthrough,\u201d he added.\nLaGuardia assailed criticism of\nthe Government\u2019s spending pro\ngram.\n\u201cThe people who cry the most\nagaint Government spending\nare the first ones to cry out if\nthe spending program is re\nduced,\u201d he said. \u2018Balancing the\nbudget doesn\u2019t bring about re\ncovery. It is recovery that\nbrings about a balanced budget.\u201d\nASKS UNIFORM WPA POLICY\n\nLaGuardia called for a \"uniform\nI\nWPA policy\u201d to equalize the ratio\nbetween Federal, state and,local 1\ncontributions.\nIn answer to questions by\nj Senator Clark (D.i of Missouri,\n1 [LaGuardia said that New York\ni; city\u2019s ratio is 39 per cent of WPA\nfunds.\n\u201cThat\u2019s lust my kick.\u2019\u2019 lua-\n1 Guardia said. \u2018WPA Is taking\ncare of ail employables, and in j\nTORPEDO PLANT\nAT ALEXANDRIA\nIS APPROVED\nReopening of Station\nI To Employ 1,000\nReestablishment of, a torpedo]\nfactory in Alexandria. Va.. is pro I\nvided for In the 1939 Navy appro\npriation bill reported to Congress\nI today.\nThe bill appropriates $1,277,000\ninitially to equip and to get the\nj establishment at Alexandria into\nproduction. It is contemplated\nthat a later expenditure of $1,229.\n000 will be appropriated com\nIpletely to equip the station.\nTO EMPLOY 1.000\nApproximately 1.000 men will\nbe employed at the Alexandria\nI plant, where it is contemplated\nproduction will be two-fifths of the\n'entire torpedo production in the\nI country.\nReestablishment of the Alexan\ndria plant is occasioned by a tor\ni pedo shortage at the Naval Tor\npedo Station in Newport. R. 1.,\nwhich is now operating on three\nI shifts a day. It is planned that\n(the Alexandria plant will work on\none shift at least until 1944. The\n-report states:\n\u201cReopening Alexandria offers\nthe most economical and expe\nditious solution to the torpedo\nshortage problem.\u201d\nShot by Sniper\nD.C.Pedestrian V ictim\nOs Auto Marksman\nA mysterious sniper last night\nwounded Robert Boardman. 48. of\n900 block. G PI. N. W.. as he\nwalked near the Hamilton Hotel'\nat Fourteenth and K Sts. N. W. j\nBoardman said he heard a re-\nport, similar to a gunshot, from a\npassing^sedan..and felt a sudden\n\u201csting\u201d in his leg. Going into a\ndrug store, he discovered blood\nstreaming from a wound.\nAt Emergency Hospital phy\nsicians extracted a 22-caliber bul\nlet from Boardman\u2019s leg. Police\n'were searching for the car today,\nj but neither they nor Boardman\ncould give any motive.\n5 Perish in Fire\nBlamed on Flue\nI FRANKLIN. N. J.. Jan. 17\n(I.N.S.). \u2014A defective chimney or\n1 flue was blamed today for the\nI fire in which a 76 year-old father,\nJames Congleton, and four of his\nchildren were burned to death as\nthey slept in their frame house\nj here Saturday nigat. The five\nwill be buried in a single grave\ntomorrow.\nDuce Cails Parley\nTo Discuss Defense\nROME, Jan. 17 (l.N.S.)\u2014The\nsupreme oommittee of defense\nwill meet in secret February 3 at\nthe Palazzo Venezia, Premier Mus\nsolini announced today. The com\nmittee is expected to discuss Italy\u2019s\nMediterranean and Far Eastern\nI plans and new increases in land\nland sea forces.\nNew York thfe city has not the\nmoney to do so.\n\u201cNew York city has been\nhardest hit, and I don\u2019t care\nwhat the ratio is but make it\nuniform.\u2019\u2019\nLaGuardia said that in 1938\nNew York city is prepared to con\ntribute $39,441,301 as its share\nof scheduled WPA allotments,\n\u201cproviding I get the same employ\nment ratio as other states. I am\nwilling to increase the ante if I\nget the same treatment.\u201d\nFIGURES CHALLENGED\nSenator Byrnes (D.) of South\nCarolina, chairman of the com\nmittee. argued with LaGuardia\nover the ratio of relief funds paid\nby New York city. The mayor,\nhowever, challenged the accuracy\nof WPA figures, which Byrnes said\nshowed that New York city\u2019s ratio\nwas one-half of 1 per cent.\nLaGuardia said he favored plac\ning all work relief projects under\nState or local supervision under\nGovernment control. He also urged\nuniformity in old age pension pay\nments, and child labor laws.\nThe mayor also recommended a\nuniform wage and hour law to\nstabilize the nation\u2019s economic\ncondition.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, MONDAY, JANUARY 17, 193*\nMMW Ofc foJW\nBy JOHN O\u2019DONNBLL AND DORIS FLEESON\nQuarterback Roosevelt called a safe, sane and sagacious\nplay for his New Deal team when he sent Solicitor Gen\neral Stanley Reed over the Supreme Court goal line. The\ncontrast between Reed\u2019s straight line-plunge, a little to the\nright of the New Deal center, and the President's flashy i\nforward pass to Left End Hugo Black is complete to the\npoint of being highly amusing.\nF. D. R. also took the precaution this time of telling the j\nnews to Press Secretary Steve Early so that Steve could j\ntip off the correspondents. An hour before the Black ap- i\npointment reached Capitol Hill Sieve still was assuring re-\nporters in his office that a long list of possible Supreme\nCourt appointees was still being cheeked over.\nIt\u2019s still a good bet, too. that\nwhen the expected resignations\nof Justices Cardozo, Brandeis\nand Mc\u00dfeyn\nolds arrive\nat the White\nHouse. Circuit\nCou.i Judge\nFlorence Al\nwill be the\nfirst woman\nnamed to the\nnation\u2019s high\nest bench.\nReed\u2019s\nclerks are\nwondering if\nthe solicitor- general will\nmodernize the high court to\nthe extent of teaching the Jus\ntices to work to radio music as\nhe himself does. F. D. R.\u2019s new\nappointee is especially fond of\nclassical and operatic music and\nnever permits his work to inter\nfere with his listening to it. And\nhis secretaries have learned to\ntiptoe around while their bass\noils his mental processes with\nthe radioed strains of Wagner\nand Beethoven.\nWliat happens at Cabinet\nmeetings is a deep secret, the\noretically but word has leaked\nout that the girls and their\nsilk stockings have nearly\ncaused a Cabinet crisis.\nIt seems several of the secre\ntaries gravely reported that\ngirl employes, hot over the\nbombing of the Panay and Jap\nanese aggression, had deter\nmined to ape Vassar and Smith\nand initiate a \"lisle-hose-only\u2019'\ncampaign in Government of\nfices. This was unwelcome\nnews to F. D. R. and stately\nSecretary of State Cordell Hull\nwho prefer peace to war fervor\nif they can get it.\nResult:\nWord has been quietly dis\nseminated in the Federal of\nfices that it is entirely patriotic\nto wear silk stockings\u2014and the\nless said about it the better.\nA recent New Dealer to run\nafoul of the lovely ladies and\ntheir whims is Housing Adminis-\ntrator Nathan\nStraus. The\nthin faced\nserious New\nYorker caused\nhis personnel\ndirector to in\ntimate to the\nHousing Ad\nministration's\ngirl employes\nthat the ad\nm i nistrator\u2019s\npersonal taste\nran to conser-\nvative dress and no blood-red\nfinger nails in office work.\nFORD SPEAKER\nSTRIKES AT CIO\nDETROIT. -lan. 17 <I.N.S.).\nHenry Ford, through an official\nspokesman, today was accusing\nthe CIO of driving public confi\ndence to cover and contributing\nto the business recession.\nAfter declaring productive busi\nness had great confidence on the\nimmediate future and denying\ncapital was on a \u201csit-down strike,\u201d\nWilliam J. Cameron, secretary to\nFord, declared in his regular Sun\nday broadcast:\n\u201cAnother thing: We cannot\ngo on in this country with the\ndaily paper and hourly radio re\nporting that great funds are be\ning collected to tie up this or\nthat industry, giving currency to\nIrresponsible and unfulfillable\nthreats to close up small supply\nshops, in order to bring big\nshops to heel\u2014we cannot circu\nlate this news' day in and day\nout for months without driving\npublic confidence to cover.\n\u201cAnything that decreases pub\nlic confidence affects the local\nmerchant\u2019s daily sales, and\nbrings down the nation a busi\nness,\u201d\nThe girls promptly countered\nwith queries as to whether this\nis or is not a free country.\nThereupon the personnel chief\u2019s\nsuggestions were quickly soft\npedaled.\nAdministrator Straus, inci- i\ndentally, was somewhat startled\nlast week when he received a\ni wire from Reno, Nev., officials\nasking how to set up a housing\nauthority and share in the Gov-\nI ernment housing subsidy. Straus\nis having divorce statistics\nI looked up to see whether the di\nvorce mecca is a good risk.\nI\nEbullient Tommy Corcoran,\nidea man for the President, has\nunofficially assumed charge of\nJr\nStan Uy- Reed\nAssistant At\ntorney Gen\neral Bob\nJackson' s\ncampaign for\nthe Demo\ncratic nomi\nnation for\ngovernor of\nNew York.\nThe results\nare a blazing\nheadache to\nthe practical\npoliticians of the New Deal\nwho would like to put over\nthe President's choice if they\ncan. First of all they'd like\na few poultices of silence to\nheal the bruises of Jackson\u2019s\nbrilliant and fighting speeches.\n\u201cHe thinks too much; such\nmen are dangerous.\u201d is a good\naxiom for candidates to ponder,\naccording to the hard-boiled\nvote purveyors.\nThe Capital is wondering why\nPostmaster General James A.\nFarley, first Catholic in the\nCabinet in' 47 idars, has not\nreceived Notre Dame's laetare\ni medal, annually awarded to an\noutstanding Catholic layman.\nFarley is high in the President's\nconfidence, does a good job m\nthe Post Office Department,\nand his private life is exem-\nI plary.\nEuthanasia Group\nSeeking Members\nNEW YORK. Jan. 17 (1.N.5.).\nOrganization of a national group,\nto legalize \u2018\u2018mercy killings\u201d of per\nsons suffering from incurable dis\neases. was pushed today by Dr.\nCharles Francis Potter, leader of\nthe first humanist society of New\nYork.\nThe organization to be known\nas the National Society for the\nLegalization of Euthanasia, will\nstage an educational campaign\nand introduce bills on the subject\nin State legislatures and Congress.\nFt 1\nit'\nKi\nJgmfa A. FarUy\nJANUARY\n(S-s\nFURNITURE\nNOVELTIES\nI FIFSKS The items in this sale\nsnric are from \u00b0ur own\nSLA Jr Ao stock. This nwnK\nCHAIRS quality at a price.\nTABLES CHARGE ACCOUNTS\nINVITED\nCATLIN\u2019S\nLighting Fixtures\n1324 NEW YORK AVE.\nNAtional 0992\nI RKiSTFRED A j CL CQHVEMttMT\nORTOHETMSI aT RAYMMTS\ni I\nREPEAL OF TAX\nON PROFITS AND\nCAPITAL URGED\nM.L.Seidman Says Move\nVital to Cure 'Slump\u2019\nBy WILLIAM S. NEAL\n(1.N.5.) Outright repeal of the\nundistributed profits and capital\n\u25a0gains taxes was urged upon the\nHouse Ways and Means Commit\ntee today by M. L. Seidman. of\nthe New York board of trade.\nappearing as the first spokesman\n'for business on the proposed new\ntax program.\nWhile praising some Ways and\nMeans subcommittee recommenda\ntions and approving Underscore\ntary of the Treasury Magill\u2019s pro\nposed future tax revision. Seidman\ninsisted the proposed program is\ninsufficient,\n\"The great majority of your\nrecommendations can only com\nmand the praise and commenda\ntion,\" said Seidman. He then\nattacked the subcommittee re\nport for failure to recommend\nrepeal of the two important\nbusiness taxes.\n\u201cI am not here tn prolong\nthe controversy as to whether\nor not these taxes were respon\nsible for our present business\nrecession,\" said Seidman. \"We\nall know it\u2019s a fact that a seri\nous business recession is upon\nus.\n\"The great majority of busi\nness men believe these two taxes\nhad much to do with the dis\ntortion of our capital economy\nand breaking down of confi\ndence.\n\"So thoroughly is business\nconvinced of this that the need\nfor immediate repeal of the un\ndistributed profits tax, as a\nbusiness stimulant, has become\nan obsession.\n\u2018\u2018To my mind the wisest thing\nyou can do in the revision of our\ntax laws and the sweetest music\nyou can send to the business ear\nis to say in a loud, clear voice, j\nThe undistributed profits tax is\nhereby repealed\u2019.\u201d\nhl\nKolM\u00bbrt .larkeon\nTrw a? te o O\n\"ItKijMwEK Ar IdZu r\nExceptional Savings on\nMEN\u2019S FURNISHINGS\nand Clothing during this Twice-a-Year\nCLEARANCE\n$1.65 5H1RT5.,.,.,.., i q\nId whit* broadcloth, both neck- B\nhand and collar attached atylee.\nSixes 13% to 17% in th* group. for $7.00\n$2.00 SHIRTS,.., e-j eq\nIncluding hirb-grade -woven I\naiadras and fine quality broad\ncloth! Regular collar, button\ndown and tab* British stripes.\nchecks, pin stripes, candy stripes. T or Jrr.JU\nAll sixes.\n$2.50 SHIRTS e-| yQ\nBeautifully woven -white broad\ncloth and fancy madras, tailored -A\nwith unusual care. Al! size* tn j r trie\nthe lot. J for VJ.ZJ\nReq. $3.50 Shirtt f/nti Nerktiet. Nw $2.65\nSI.OO NECKTIES,, ZQ\nEvery tie handmade! Wool lined! JJr Cz\nKeailieni construction! The seise\ntion include* some woo! neckties. for $3.75\nMEN\u2019S HOSE OO\nA special group of rayon, liele and \u00a3J J C\njacquard silk socks\u2014all made to S\nsei! for considerably more than this x Z C/l\nmost modest price. for qtI.DU\n$1.95 PAJAMAS,., e-| J.O\nFancy or plain broadcloth In I\nmiddy and coat atylea with con-\ntraetinr trim Full cut and vary 3 z ,r\nwell tailored. J J or fr.ij\n$14,95 and $17,95 ROBES\nFamous $14.95 Rabb or F*\nSuskanna and Devonshire fl* alk Ifewk\nRohes and Regal Lounge I\nJackets and $17.95 Regal I B\nRobes\u2014all full lined.\nUse Our Convenient\n\u201cJin 3 charge plan\u201d\nTalapAeaa REonblit 1334\n\u2018Dummy CCC\u2019Theft\nBlame Laid to War\nDept, by Park Head\nDemar ay Says Army Disbursing Unit\nShould Have Caught Stitely\n(1.N.5.) Blaine for embezzlement of upwards of $85,000\nfrom the Government through a dummy CCC camp, was laid\non the War Department today by A. E. Demaray, associate di\nrector of the National Park Service.\nTestifying before the Senate'\nPublic Lands Committee, Demaray\ninsisted that the National Park\nService, in which Renot Stitely.\n[former employe, operated the\nimaginary camp, was not negli\ngent in its checking system.\nStitely has pleaded guilty in\ncourt here to embezzlement of the\nCCC funds. The War Depart\nment disbursing office should have\ndiscovered Stitely\u2019s defalcations,\n(which ran for over three years.\nDemaray told the committee.\nPITTMAN CHALLENGES HIM\nSenator Pittman <D.) of Nevada\nchallenged Demaray\u2019s contention.\nThe War Department did not keep\nbooks on the CCC transactions\nother than records of disburse\nment, Pittman said.\nThe committee\u2019s inquiry into\nthe embezzlement of Government\nmoney was hinged on its investiga\ntion of the qualifications of Ebert\nK. Burlew for the office of First\nAssistant Secretary of the Interior.\nPittsman and other Senators\nopposed to Burlew\u2019s confirmation\nwere attempting to show ineffi\nciency on the part of Bullew in\nhis present position as first ad\nministrative assistant to Secretary\nIckes.\nLACKED MANPOWER\nTestimony was given by Dema\nray that the accounting depart\nment in the Interior Department\nwas undermanned. Replying to\nPittman. Demaray said that Bur\nlew made up the budget for the\naccounting department.\nWhen Demaray said the Park\nService balanced its books annual\nly, Pittman asked:\n\u201cDo you mean to say that\nunder your system you could\ndiscover a shortage?\u201d\nI \u201cYes.\u201d\nThen Pittman reminded De-\nH,\nt CLOItaNG.;\ni-?' sis R i; f' \u00aes:< 'i\u00ae\nRe Su hr $29.75\ne-Y'A'7C\n|_wpw\nat sA\nx J|:.\nIT\u2122\u2019 i\n[MER\nJATCI\nPAY PAY i/ 3 PAY l/ 3\nFeb. 15th Mar. 15th A prill sth\niMaray that Stitely had operated\nI his imaginary camp for embezzle\nment purposes for more than three\nyears.\nEVEN RAISED TWO\nThere was a ripple of laughter\nin the hearing room when De\narray said Stitely had the \u201caudac\nity\u201d to raise the pay of two of the\nfictitious persons in his \u201cacmp,\u201d\nwhich theoretically existed in the\nShenandoah National Park in Vir\nginia.\n\u201cDon\u2019t you think the Park\nService was very careless in this\nmatter,\" asked Pittman of De\nmaray.\n\u201cI don\u2019t believe so.\u201d replied\nDemaray. \u201cI think we have\nbeen as carefu las humanly pos\nsible. I admit we were slow\nin catching this defalcation.\nI but we have caught others in\nthe past.\"\nTUITION BILL\nHERE IS PUSHED\nWith the sanction of the Budg\net Bureau, the Commissioners to\nday urged Congress to enact\nbill prohibiting the free admis\nsion of nonresident students in\nDistrict public schools.\nThe bureau concurred in the\nCommissioners\u2019 opinion that such\na bill would aid in reducing con\ngestion in the District school sys\ntem. Under present practices,\n\u2022children whase parents work in\nWashington but who reside out\nside the city are allowed to attend\nlocal schools without cost.\nThe Budget Bureau also ap\nproved a bill providing for the\nestablishment of a division in the\nTraffic Bureau to record liens on\nautomobiles for a fee of 50 cents.\nThe Recorder of Deeds now re\ncords such liens and charges $1.50\nto register them and $1.50 to re\n'lease them.","height":"25908","width":"20102"}}
